# AgentCAP Experiment Plan (v3)

**Paper**: "When Two Heads Are Cheaper Than One: Cost-Optimal Multi-Agent Combinations on Local GPU Clusters"
**Target**: NeurIPS 2026
**Hardware**: 4× NVIDIA RTX PRO 6000 (98GB VRAM each)
**Serving**: SGLang, all local inference, cost = GPU-seconds

---

## Core Thesis

On local GPU clusters, multi-agent combination strategies can beat single large models on cost-accuracy Pareto efficiency. The advantage comes from **conditional compute allocation** — routing easy tasks to cheap models, hard tasks to expensive ones — not from models "discussing" with each other. This advantage saturates at ~2 agents; adding a 3rd provides diminishing returns because most tasks are either trivially easy or globally unsolvable, leaving only a narrow "boundary" zone where extra agents help.

---

## Three Research Questions

### RQ1: Which multi-agent combinations sit on the accuracy-cost Pareto frontier?

**What we test**: 6 strategies × 4+ model pairs × 2 benchmarks.
**Expected finding**: Cascade (small → large with confidence routing) is consistently Pareto-optimal across model families. Budget-matched Best-of-N-Small beats single-large models.
**Why it matters**: Practitioners deploying local GPU clusters need a simple, universal recommendation. If cascade dominates regardless of model family, that's directly actionable.
**Key figure**: Pareto frontier overlay across all model pairs.

### RQ2: Does model diversity improve multi-agent outcomes — and where does the value come from?

**What we test**: Compare homogeneous strategies (3× same model) vs heterogeneous strategies (3 different models from different families). Test whether diversity's value is in **answer aggregation** (cross-family vote) or **uncertainty estimation / routing** (diversity-gated cascade).
**Expected finding**: Diversity helps routing more than aggregation. Two cheap diverse models disagreeing is a stronger escalation signal than single-model confidence.
**Why it matters**: This is the key novelty — most multi-agent work uses identical agents. We show that heterogeneity's real value is as a cost-free uncertainty detector, not as an ensemble.
**Key figure**: Homogeneous vs heterogeneous vote/cascade cost-accuracy comparison.

### RQ3: Why do returns saturate after two agents?

**What we test**: 3-tier cascade (small → medium → large) vs 2-tier cascade. Task-level decomposition into easy / boundary / unsolvable categories.
**Expected finding**: Most tasks fall into "small-model-easy" or "globally-unsolvable". Only ~10-15% of tasks sit in the "boundary" zone where extra compute helps. A 3rd tier adds negligible value because the boundary is too narrow.
**Why it matters**: Explains *why* the title holds — two heads are enough because the decision boundary is thin. Provides theoretical grounding, not just empirical observation.
**Key figure**: Task difficulty decomposition (easy/boundary/unsolvable) with strategy accuracy overlay.

---

## Strategies

### 2-Model Strategies (Existing, Implemented)

| Strategy | Type | How it works | Role |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Cascade** | Multi-agent | Small tries first; escalate to large if confidence < threshold | Core strategy |
| **Adaptive-Cascade** | Multi-agent | Like cascade but threshold adapts based on task difficulty signals | Core strategy |
| **Vote** | Multi-agent | 3× small model, majority vote | Baseline |
| **Generate-Verify** | Multi-agent | Small generates, large verifies and accepts/rejects | Core strategy |
| **Best-of-N** | Single-agent | N× same model, pick best by heuristic | Control |
| **Self-Critique** | Single-agent | Same model critiques and revises its own output | Control (negative) |

### >2 Model Strategies (New — RQ2 & RQ3)

| Strategy | Models | How it works | Tests |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Diversity-Gated Cascade** ⭐ | 2 cheap (different families) + 1 large | Two cheap models solve in parallel. If they **agree** → accept. If they **disagree** → escalate to large model. | RQ2: Is cross-family disagreement a better routing signal than single-model confidence? |
| **Cross-Family Vote** | 3 models (different families) | Three different models vote (e.g., Qwen3-4B + GPT-OSS-20b + Nemotron-3-Nano). Compare vs 3× same model. | RQ2: Does architectural diversity improve vote accuracy at same GPU-second budget? |
| **3-Tier Cascade** | small + medium + large (same family) | Small → medium → large, with confidence routing at each tier. | RQ3: Does finer-grained conditional compute outperform 2-tier, or do returns plateau? |

**Diversity-Gated Cascade** is the flagship new strategy. The other two are controls.

---

## Available Models

All models fit on 1 GPU (98GB). Cost measured in GPU-seconds of active inference.

| Model | Family | Architecture | Active Params | BF16 Size | Status |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| Qwen3-4B | Qwen3 | Dense Transformer | 4B | 7.6 GB | ✅ Cached |
| Qwen3-30B-A3B | Qwen3 | MoE | 3B active | 57 GB | ✅ Cached |
| Qwen3-32B | Qwen3 | Dense Transformer | 32B | 62 GB | ✅ Cached |
| Qwen3.5-9B | Qwen3.5 | Dense + DeltaNet | 9B | ~18 GB | To download |
| GPT-OSS-20b | OpenAI | MoE | 3.6B active | ~42 GB | To download |
| Nemotron-3-Nano | NVIDIA | MoE + Mamba hybrid | 3B active | ~57 GB | To download |

### Why These Models

- **3 families** (Qwen, OpenAI, NVIDIA): Different training data, tokenizers, architectures
- **3 architecture types** (Dense, MoE, MoE+Mamba): Tests whether strategy effectiveness is architecture-dependent
- **All ~3-4B active params** for small models: Fair cost comparison (similar inference cost per token)
- **Medium models** (9B): Enables 3-tier cascade experiments

---

## Experiment Design

### Benchmarks

| Benchmark | Type | Tasks | Evaluation | Why |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **BigCodeBench** (ICML 2024) | Non-agentic code generation | 50 tasks | Execution-based (unittest) | Single-turn, deterministic eval, widely cited |
| **MCP-Atlas** (Scale AI, 2025-2026) | Agentic multi-tool orchestration | 50 tasks | Claims-based with GPT-4o judge | Multi-turn tool-use, tests real-world agent capability |

### Metrics (Paper-Level)

| Metric | Definition | Why |
|---|---|---|
| **Pass@1** | % tasks solved correctly | Primary accuracy measure |
| **GPU-s/task** | GPU-seconds per task (inference time × GPU count) | Primary cost measure |
| **Cost/Correct** | GPU-s per correctly solved task | Pareto efficiency |
| **tool_call_count** | Number of tool invocations (MCP-Atlas only) | Agentic complexity measure |

### Phase 1: 2-Model Experiments (6 strategies × model pairs)

| Pair | Small | Large | Key Question | Benchmark | Status |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **A** | Qwen3-4B | Qwen3-30B-A3B | Baseline: big capability gap, same family | BigCodeBench | ✅ Done |
| **B** | Qwen3-30B-A3B | Qwen3-32B | Does cascade help when models are close in ability? | Both | 🔄 Running |
| **C** | GPT-OSS-20b | Qwen3.5-9B | Cross-family: does cascade generalize? | Both | ⏳ Next |
| **D** | Nemotron-3-Nano | Qwen3.5-9B | Cross-architecture: Mamba+MoE as cheap router | Both | ⏳ Next |

### Phase 2: >2 Model Experiments (3 new strategies)

| Experiment | Models | GPUs | Key Question (RQ) | Benchmark |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Diversity-Gated Cascade** | Qwen3-4B + GPT-OSS-20b → Qwen3-32B | 3 GPUs | Cross-family disagreement as routing signal (RQ2) | BigCodeBench |
| **Diversity-Gated Cascade** | Qwen3-4B + Nemotron-3-Nano → Qwen3-32B | 3 GPUs | Same, with Mamba hybrid (RQ2) | BigCodeBench |
| **Cross-Family Vote** | Qwen3-4B + GPT-OSS-20b + Nemotron-3-Nano | 3 GPUs | Diverse vote vs homogeneous Best-of-N (RQ2) | BigCodeBench |
| **3-Tier Cascade** | Qwen3-4B → Qwen3.5-9B → Qwen3-32B | 3 GPUs | Does 3rd tier help or saturate? (RQ3) | BigCodeBench |
| **Diversity-Gated Cascade** | Best config from above | 3 GPUs | Does it hold for agentic tasks? | MCP-Atlas |

**Budget-matching rule**: All comparisons normalized to equal GPU-seconds. For example, cross-family vote (3 cheap models) compared against Best-of-N-Small (3× same cheap model) at same total cost.

---

## Confirmed Results (Pair A)

| Strategy | Accuracy | GPU-s/task | Cost/Correct | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Best-of-N-Small (4B×3) | 50% | 104.4 | 208.9 | Cheap×3 > Expensive×1 |
| Cascade | 44% | 23.9 | **54.3** | Pareto-optimal |
| Best-of-N-Large (30B×3) | 44% | 74.7 | 169.8 | |
| Adaptive-Cascade | 42% | 41.6 | 99.1 | |
| Vote | 36% | 25.3 | 70.2 | |
| Generate-Verify | 30% | 25.1 | 83.5 | |
| Self-Critique-Small | 24% | 52.4 | 218.3 | Hurts vs 30% base |
| Self-Critique-Large | 14% | 23.6 | 168.3 | Hurts vs 38% base |

**Oracle ceiling**: 56% (44% of tasks unsolvable by any strategy)
**Cascade routing**: When small model doesn't escalate → 100% correct. When escalated → only 17.6% correct.

